					<div lang="en" dir="ltr" class="mw-content-ltr"><p>Additional Background Material for Drugs and the Brain, Week 4</p>
<h1> <span class="mw-headline" id="Alzheimer.27s_disease">Alzheimer's disease</span></h1>
<hr />
<h1> <span class="mw-headline" id="Parkinson.27s_disease">Parkinson's disease</span></h1>
<hr />
<p><strong>Therapeutic use of Deep brain stimulation (DBS) in Parkinson's disease (and optogenetics)</strong><br />
<ul><li> I found a fascinating paper on the therapeutic use of Deep brain stimulation (DBS) in Parkinson's disease. This paper is also an interesting introduction to the use of <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Optogenetics">optogenetics</a> from Karl Deisseroth's lab at Stanford.</p>
</li></ul>

<ul>
<li><a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="http://www.stanford.edu/group/dlab/papers/Gradinaru%20Science%202009.pdf">Gradinaru et al. Science 2009</a> <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/19299587">PubMed abstract</a>  </li>
<li><p>Gradinaru V, Mogri M, Thompson KR, Henderson JM, Deisseroth K. Optical deconstruction of parkinsonian neural circuitry. Science. 2009 Apr
17;324(5925):354-9. doi: 10.1126/science.1167093. Epub 2009 Mar 19. PubMed PMID: 19299587.</p></li>
<li><p>The <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="http://www.stanford.edu/group/dlab/index.html">Deisseroth Lab</a> home page (and research) is also worth checking out</p></li>
</ul>

